In LaTeX, automatic generation of a table of contents (TOC) is achieved using the `\tableofcontents` command and configuring `\documentclass` and `\RunWithPackages` (usually `bookmark` and `tocloft` for advanced customization). Here's a comprehensive example:

**Minimal Template:**
```latex
\documentclass[11pt,openright]{book}
\usepackage{tocloft} % advanced TOC customization
\usepackage{bookmark} % improve bookmarking
\usepackage{kantlipsum} % dummy text filler

\begin{document}

\RunWithPackages % process packages affecting TOC

\tableofcontents % generate table of contents

\part{Introduction}
\kant[1] % dummy content

\section{Background}
\kant[2]
\subsection{Importance}
\kant[3]
\subsubsection{Why}
\kant[4]

\part{Application}
\section{Implementation}
\kant[5]
\subsection{Details}
\kant[6]

\backmatter
\appendix
\section{Additional Resources}
\kant[7]

\end{document}
```
**How it works:**

1. **Document class:** Choose a suitable class (in this case, `book`) that supports parts, sections, and chapters.
2. **Packages:** Load `tocloft` for advanced TOC customization (e.g., modifying toc layout, section depths) and `bookmark` to improve bookmarking and TOC generation.
3. **`\RunWithPackages`:** Process packages affecting the TOC (optional, but recommended).
4. **`\tableofcontents`:** Insert this command where you want the TOC to appear in your document. LaTeX will automatically generate the table of contents based on the sectioning commands used throughout the document (e.g., `\part`, `\section`, `\subsection`, etc.).

Upon compilation (e.g., `pdflatex myfile.tex`), your LaTeX document will produce a table of contents with the specified section headings and hierarchies.

Remember to update your `.tex` file accordingly by adding or removing sectioning commands to reflect your document's structure.

